column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: A contract driver connected to a trailer that was in the process of loading sodium hypochlorite - 12.5% in the inside loading bay of the Hydrite Chemical facility in Oshkosh, Wisconsin.  The driver pulled out of the loading bay with the hose still connected to the trailer and to the loading lines inside the bay.  While pulling away, the coupling on the facility loading line broke and the hose was dragged away with the trailer.  Employees stopped the driver and shut both the valves on the trailer and on the facility loading lines immediately.  Some sodium hypochlorite was released outside of the loading bay and as such outside of containment.  An estimated 33 pounds of Sodium Hypochlorite 12.5% solution were released into a stormsewer line located outside of the loading bay.  Sand bags were placed in a manhole that the stormsewer lines were connected to block the flow and the storm sewer lines and associated manhole were cleaned by North Shore Environmental Services, an environmental response/remediation company.
column169: The company supplying the driver involved in the incident was issued a corrective action request regarding the incident.  The driver will be required to demonstrate proper training and knowledge for continued work at the facility.

column168: Train 350 was setting out a bad order car when the conductor noticed tank car UTLX 203797 with product sloshing from the top of the car.  Car was placed over the spill pan and isolated.  A contractor was called to secure the car.  Investigation revealed one manway bolt finger tight and the spring on the safety valve broken.  The contractor tightened the manway bolt and the shipper was contacted to arrange for the safety valve to be replaced.  The car owner (Murex) arranged with Rescar to have the safety valve replaced.  Shipper is applying for FRA Movement Approval.    NARRI = 32
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 10/03/2012 at 1343 hours, an FRA inspector in the CSXT Montgomery, AL terminal, discovered UTLX 209319, a loaded tank car of Alcohol N.O.S., was leaking vapors from the manway area. The car was isolated and shipper, Archer Daniels Midland Company and Chemtrec (report #2012-10-03-00139), were notified. A CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found two manway bolts were less than tool tight and were marked by the FRA inspector. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper representative, John Martin 217-520-9994. The manway bolts were secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.     NARRI: 5(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80  Cause Code: 200
column169: Spoke with the shipper contact person John Martin. Suggested that the loaders lubricate the bolts and use a torque wrench to properly secure the manway bolts.

column168: During a routine dock check at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a drum containing hazardous waste was observed to have liquid on the lid and dripping down the side.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the dock personnel cleaned up the leaked material with a suitable absorbent material and spill pads.  The leaking drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the abosrbent materials used to clean up the spill.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The leak came from the gasket on the lock ring removeable head drum.  The gasket was not properly placed allowing the material to leak.  The nuts were not tightened to the specifications for closure.  The shipper was notified and the driver was cautioned to check drums more carefully at the time of pickup.

column168: Recieved a call through RMCC for leaking car UTLX 213265 in the Monroe, LA yard.  A contractor was mobilized to site for assessment.  Prior to arrival of the contractor the Louisianna State Police arrived onsite and determined the leak was originating from the liquid valve plug.  The valve handle was in the closed position.  The contractor arrived onsite, verified the valve was closed, relieved the pressure from the car and then removed the plug.  The valve was open approximately 1/4" allowing the product to release.  The valve and handle were re-aligned, plug secured, and the car wiped down.  The car was placed in HZ hold and the shipper was notified and OTMA was applied for by the shipper.

column168: Our investigation is that it was a driver error which caused the spill. According to the veeder root reading the tank was full (The veeder root reading shows that the FedEx tank could only hold 90% of 4797 apparently he was trying to put the full 7500 gallons from our tanker) According to witnesses the driver left pumps unattended (Was seen by FedEx driver Sleeping in truck) which caused the FedEx safety valve (FedEx tank has a safety valve that locks when it reaches maximum capacity)which caused extra pressure on the pump hose and released the cam lock,   the hose was ejected spilling fuel recklessly everywhere (because the driver was in truck sleeping)by the time the driver realized what was going on it was already out of hand. We assure you that disciplinary action was taken and the driver was terminated for his negligence. Driver estimated roughly 150 gals but by the time we were able to go out to site it had been cleaned up. Our equipment was checked out and mechanic said it is still working properly, and there is no way that it was defective. We still haven't recieved the total amount for damages. Once the final amount in damages is recieved we will provide a supplement in this report.
column169: Drivers are given more safety and procedure training. Made aware that they need to be next to hoses and pumps at all times and Never leave them unattended.

Local supervision placed sorbant material on the spill around container and contractor was called.  Contractor opened container and found 15 pails on a pallet which had been crushed by the weight of the pallet on top of it.  Blocking and bracing was good.  There was just too much weight piled on top of pallet.  Spill was cleaned up, empty pails removed, and leaking pails over packed.    Please note the shipper's Emeregncy Response Telephone number provided by the shipper was no good.  No one answered the phone and it went to voice mail.  Message was never returned.  Contact number was found on Internet for Hanjin who was contacted.  We did recieve an email from a company representing the customer the following day requesting information on the spill.

column168: The shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from Houston, TX on the Sydney Express Voyage 1241E as non-hazardous cargo.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Houston of undeclared hazardous material loaded in the container.    -UN1066, NITROGEN, COMPRESSED, CLASS 2.2    The shipping papers that accompanied the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and the container was not placarded and/or marked.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous material onboard.

column168: HAZMAT BOX SLID DOWN THE MISSORT SLIDE BY THE HIGH PICK. THE SLIDE WAS EMPTY, SO IT GAINED SOME SPEED BEFORE IT HIT THE BOTTOM STOP BAR. WHEN THE SUP WALKED BY, HE NOTICED THE LEAKING HAZMAT, MOVED HIS WORKERS FROM THE AREA, CLOSED THE MISSORT SLIDE AND CALLED FOR A RESPONDER. WHEN I GOT TO THE SPILL, I FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE TO THE CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET (9). I "PHED" THE LIQUID ON THE SLIDE AND THEN APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL I GOT A 7 READING. I THEN BROUGHT THE DAMAGED BOX AND LITTER BACK TO THE RESPONDER AREA TO BE "DMPED". THE SLIDE WAS REOPENED BY THE PT SUP AFTER IT WAS CLEANED.

column168: SUP. BRANDON L., AT PD-8 DOCK, WAS WALKING HIS DOCK WHEN HE NOTICED A VERY STRONG SMELL. HE TRACED THE SMELL TO THE CONCRETE GROUND NEAR BAY # 420. HE DECIDED IT WAS A LEAKING HAZMAT. BRANDON TURNED OFF ALL THE DOCK'S BELTS, HAD HIS WORKERS MOVE TO AN OVERHEAD TRUCK DOOR, AND CALLED FOR A RESPONDER. WHEN I ARRIVED, I FOLLOWED THE CORROSIVE 8 LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET AND APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE. I ALSO HAD BRANDON MOVE MORE FEEDERS OFF THE WALL SO MORE AIR COULD ENTER. WHEN THE PH WAS IN A NEUTRAL (7) RANGE, AND THE FLOOR WAS CLEANED, I BROUGHT THE DAMAGED HAZMAT BACK TO THE RESPONDER PIT TO BE "DMPED".

column168: BOX WAS BROUGHT TO CLERKS AREA FROM THE ORANGE BELT BY A PART TIME SUPERVISOR, CHEMICAL WAS NOT LEAKING AS A LIQUID BUT THE BOX IT WAS IN WAS TOTALLY FALLING APART, BRITTLE TO TOUCH AND DISINTEGRATING, VERY BRITTLE. POSSIBLE THAT VAPORS LEAKED FROM THE BOTTLES DURING TRANSPORT THAT EFFECTED THE BOX COMPOSITION, THUS CAUSING BOX TO BECOME BRITTLE AND FALL APART. AT NO TIME COULD ANYONE NOTICE A SMELL, ODOR, OR VAPORS COMING FROM THE CHEMICAL BUT THIS IS THE 4TH SHIPMENT OF SAME CHEMICAL IN 2 WEEKS THAT THE BOXES FELL APART UPON ARRIVAL IN THE HUB, AND NONE COULD BE SHIPPED ANY FURTHER DUE TO THE CONDITION OF THEIR OUTER BOX. VWR IS THE SHIPPER AND SINCE THEY DO NOT ACCEPT ANY HAZMAT DRUMS, ALL 4 BOTTLES WILL BE PLACED IN DMP CAGE.
column169: LOOK INTO WHY BOXES ARE FALLING APART WHEN SHIPPING THIS SAME CHEMICAL, 4 TIMES IN 2 WEEKS, POSSIBLY LIDS ON BOTTLES ARE FAULTY.

column168: I WAS CONTACTED BY THE SORT AISLE SUPERVISOR OF A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE MOTHER BELT OF THE SORT AISLE. I SUITED UP IN FULL PPE AND HEADED TO THE SPILL LOCATION. UPON REACHING THE LOCATION THE BELTS WERE OFF AND THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE WITH THE ORIENTATION ARROWS FACING SIDEWAYS. THE PACKAGE WAS WET AT THE CORNER WITH LEAKAGE ON THE BELT AND IT WAS LABELED WITH A FLAMMABLE LIQUID 3 DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL. I REFERRED TO MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR CORRECT PROCEDURE TO HANDLE A FLAMMABLE LIQUID SPILL AND CLEANED UP THE LEAKAGE ON THE BELT. THE PACKAGE HAD A NOTICABLE ODOR SO I PUT ON MY REFLECTIVE YARD VEST AND I COMPLETED THE DMP PROCESS IN A MORE VENTILLATED AREA OUTSIDE THE BUILDING. AFTER I FINISHED BAGGING THE SPILL I TRANSPORTED EVERYTHING TO THE DMP CAGE TO BE ENTERED INTO THE COMPUTER.

column168: During a routine yard inspection, NATX 300978 was found to have wet product on the side of the car.  On inspection of the car it was determined to have a leak originating from the manway  with approximately 2 - 2 1/2 gallons of product on the side of the car.  One of eight manway swing bolts was less than tool tight.  The manway gasket was inspected and found to be in good condition.  The manway was properly secured and the car wiped dry.  There also appeared to be a weeping leak from under the vapor valve.  The valve was turned approximately 1/4 turn.  The car was set out and re-inspected on 10/16/2012 at 1700 hours and found to have no leaks.  The manway was sealed and the car returned to transportation.

During a routine yard check at the ten day storage lot at the intended waste disposal facility, a rolloff box containing what was described as a solid was observed leaking liquid which had apparently separated from the solidified material.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and began containing and cleaning up the spilled material with suitable absorbents, which by this time had streamed onto the neighboring property.  No waterways nor stormwater drains were affected.  The material was cleaned up and all contaminated soil placed into the rolloff box which was expedited for immediate processing at the intended waste disposal facility.  TCEQ was notified as well as the NRC as the material exceeded the RQ of 10 pounds.  TCEQ incident number 174967.

column168: Shipper came to the cargo office to tender his shipment.  He said they were water samples...going to ANC.  I did the airway bill while Kirk did the normal cargo screening on the package.  There were two coolers...atleast one cooler was opened, so Kirk gave him some tape to secure his shipment.  He did not indicate to us that there was any hazmat in his shipment...and signed the paperwork as such.    Several hours later, the ticket counter called over to ask if we had accepted a shipment from Mr. Braunstein...I said we had received a shipment of water samples.  They were sitting in our cooler waiting for an evening flight to ANC.  They told me that they had refused the shipment as baggage due to hazmat items inside the coolers.  We went out to the cooler and since the custody seal had already been broken, we opened and inspected the packages...they had bottles with liquid inside that had Hydrocloric acid and Nitric acid labels on the lids.  We withdrew the shipment and blocked the manifest so it would not be transported.  I contacted the shipper and advised them of the situation.  They would be getting back to us.
column169: Advise shipper to declare Haz-Mat

column168: An operator at the TRANSFLO-Birmingham transloading terminal was conducting a transload of Ferric Chloride from Railcar TILX 110040 to a cargo tank. The transfer was about 50% complete when the product (Ferric Chloride) began to leak between the railcar product flange and the unloading connection flange that had been attached to the railcar for transloading. The employee supervising the transfer went on top of the railcar to shut the transfer down. As he got to the flange to shut the valve off, one of the 4 bolts that hold the flange to the railcar pulled through the flange hole on the railcar flange connection. And since the railcar had been pressurized with air for this transfer, the result was that product sprayed out of the flange hole on the railcar. The supervising employee forced the flange down and then opened the air valve to release the air off the railcar. Once the air pressure was relieved from the railcar, the release of product stopped. Approximately 20 gallons of Ferric Chloride was released. Supervising employee was not injured. No product was released off-site or impacted any waterways or drains. An environmental remediation company was called to assist in the clean-up of the released material.     AWARENESS ITEMS:   1. Two transfers of product were unloaded from the railcar the day before without a release of product.   2.Upon inspection after the release it was determined that the flange bolts were missing two of the four washers on arrival.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:     1.EQUIPMENT FAILURE- Inadequate tools and equipment.  There is no specified standard for securement of the 4 bolt flange to the railcar.      CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:   1. Make recommendation to TRANSFLO equipmennt manager that a larger, ½ moon shaped metal plate be used on all 4 bolt flange fittings to secure the transloading fitting to railcar.

column168: At approximately 1:30 PM CST, a strong odor was reported to be coming from tank car GATX 31633 in the Laredo yard in Laredo, TX. Emergency notifications were made and emergency responders were activated. Responders arrived at 1:55 PM CST and met with appropriate KCS personnel. The tankcar was secured and responders began root cause investigation.    Upon further inspection of the car, it was determined that lading was dripping from the Bottom Outlet Valve (BOV) secondary containment cap reducer unloading plug and that the plug was just barely threaded on. It was also noted that the manway on top of the tankcar had 4 loose manway bolts (3 swingbolts in the down position). The plug was tightened with a 24-inch pipe wrenchand the cap secured tightly. Also, the car was found with 1 foot+ of heel remaining in the car.    The manway bolts were tightened to tool tightness with 24-pipe wrench in the appropriate pattern. Once it was determined the leak had been stopped, the car was secured and responders demobilized.    * No injuries reported    File Note Item 19the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column25: Hyundai Intermodal Inc. for NACA Logistics USA Inc.
column168: A BNSF mechanical inspection of an inbound BNSF intermodal train revealed entrained top positioned container CAIU 805141 leaking an unknown substance from its bottom front flooring onto the bottom container it was stacked atop.  The railcar CAIU 805141 was riding upon was set-out of the train. Contract cranes lifted CAIU 805141 off the railcar and placed it over plastic sheeting for determination and remediation of the spillage. Contract responders found one 55 gallon steel drum (destined for export to the Philippines) with a crack at its lower sidewall from rubbing contact with an adjacent unit. The leaking drum was removed and placed into a disposal drum for appropriate landfill disposal. CAIU 805141 was cleaned of all spillage and other lading removed was returned inside CAIU 805141 appropriately blocked and braced. The spillage on the bottom container's exterior and the railcar was also cleaned.

column168: Trailer FSTZ 814989 that arrived on an inbound BNSF intermodal train was observed with a paint substance that leaked from this trailer onto the trailer's rear wheels and the rail flatcar it was riding atop. FSTZ 814989 was carefully deramped and placed in the facility's containment area for leak source determination and remediation of spillage. Contract responders found two palletized 5 gallon pails of paint that had been compromised at their bottom seams during in-transit load shift. These damaged pails were stacked atop a wooden pallet missing top cross slats which did not provide a stable base for lading stacked atop this pallet. Insufficient blocking and bracing was also noted at the rear of the load in FSTZ 814989. Response contractors cleaned all FSTZ 814989's  interior/exterior paint spillage, as well as the spillage on the rail flatcar. Lading removed from FSTZ 814989 was returned inside FSTZ 814989 properly block and braced for further transportation. The compromised pails were earmarked for disposal along with all the spent supplies required to clean the paint spillage.
column169: Ensure that lading within intermodal trailers/containers are properly loaded and secured for rail transit, including the use of suitable pallets for palletized lading.

column168: After loading the trailer the driver pulled out from under the loading rack and parked to go inside the office to get his paperwork. As he exited his tractor he noticed a slight drip of material coming from the valve outlet dust cap. The driver discovered that the external and internal valVes were not completely closed. At 08:45 hours on October 21, 2012, it was discovered that tank car IAPX 1037, an argon liquid load, was venting and ice forming underneath in Port Arthur, TX in Zone 4 Track 104.  The car was isolated, appropriate notifications were made, and emergency responder was activated.    Upon further inspection, it was found that the shipper had offered the tank car into transportation with the "pressure build inlet valve" left in the open position. This caused liquid Argon to charge the onboard vaporizor. The onboard vaporizor is utilized for flashing the liquid to a gas for unloading to highway cargo trucks. The onboard vaporizor unit had several holes/cracks which caused the lading to release from this ancilary vaporizor unit. Also, the car was found with a depleted vacuum to the annular space which caused lading product to build pressure and occasionally vent from the regulator valve more often. The "pressure build inlet valve" was manually closed to prevent any further venting of lading from the vaporizor unit.    Air Liquide sent a representative to make sure car didnt need any further repairs before being sent to its final destination. The following day the tank car was vented of pressure and thus de-icing the half frozen regulator valve making it completely operable again.  Air liquide notified carrier that all valves and devices were working properly and that the package was DOT compliant for transportation.     *No injuries were reported    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: During normal switching operations in the railyard, tank car GATX 22463 was reported expelling product from its manway closure. All movement was stopped. A BNSF employee on the ground nearby was splashed by product droplets and immediately water flushed off impacted dermal and clothing areas with no resultant injury. Contract responders inspecting GATX 22463 found the manway securement bolts less that tool tight (some finger loose) and its manway gasket misaligned; thus preventing a good closure seal at the manway. The responders correctly positioned the serviceable manway gasket and properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts. New seal HMRI000363 was applied at the manway closure. Spillage on the sideshell was neutralized and any residual staining was cleaned.

column168: Trailer RDWY 121610 that arrived on an inbound BNSF intermodal train was observed with a green paint like substance that had leaked from this trailer's rear doorway. RDWY 121610 was carefully deramped off its rail flatcar and placed in the facility's containment/unloading dock area for leak source determination and remediation of spillage. Contract responders found one palletized 5 gallon pail of paint that had been compromised during in-transit load shift. The damaged pail sustained a bottom seam split possibly initiated by the down force of heavy lading stacked atop these palletized paint pails. Insufficient blocking and bracing was also noted at the rear of the load in RDWY 121610. Response contractors cleaned all RDWY 121610's interior/exterior paint spillage, as well as the spillage on the rail flatcar. The compromised pail was placed into an overpack drum. Lading removed from RDWY 121610 was returned inside RDWY 121610 properly blocked and braced for further transportation.

column168: A rolloff box was being delivered to the ten day storage yard at the intended waste disposal facility. column168: Container MEDU 648455 was observed leaking a clear liquid from the bottom of the container while in the unloading process at Salt Lake City, Intermodal Yard, in Salt Lake City Utah.   Leon Hendrickson, Manager of Hazardous Material was notified.  The container was isolated and Pacific West, Hazardous Material Contractor was called to respond. The container was opened revealing 72 drums stacked 2 high.  There was inadequate blocking + bracing and the drums were not palletized or banded.  There were no required labels to identify the hazardous material on any of the drums.    All 72 drums were unloaded, 18 drums were leaking from seam of the drums.  There were no DOT numbers on any drums in the shipment.  All 72 drums were placed in DOT approved over packs, palletized, banded and labeled then reloaded into containers and properly blocked and braced.    The containers were released and continued to destination.

column168: An odor was reported near the outbound tracks in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders investigated the odor source and found tank car GATX 16534 emanating commodity vapors/odor from its manway closure. No liquid commodity release was evident. Detailed inspection of the manway securement revealed the manway gasket applied was cut, torn and misaligned thus preventing a good closure seal. Responders replaced the damaged manway gasket with a suitable new manway gasket and resecured the manway lid. Afterwards, no further commodity odor/vapors were detected. Intact shipper seal KM 119423 at the manway closure was replaced by seal BNSF 06157575.

column168: A TXDOT Rail Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported observing tank car TILX 260931 with product spillage on its side shell and around the manway nozzle that emanated from TILX 260931's manway closure. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected TILX 260931 finding the installed manway gasket out of position and unserviceable, thus not providing a good manway closure seal which allowed product to escape during rail movement. The responder installed a new manway gasket and properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts. Intact manway seal 065253 removed was replaced by seal BNSF 175453. All spillage evaporated.

column168: ON OCTOBER 2, 2012 A TRANSPORTATION SERVICE UNLIMITED CARGO TANK DRIVER WAS MAKING HIS FIRST DELIVERY OF HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION TO CORAL REEF TROPICAL IN KEY LARGO. THERE IS A FILL LINE MARKED ON THE 1000 GALLON ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK THAT THE DRIVER SHOULD NOT FILL ABOVE.  THE DRIVER DELIVERED 1000 GALLONS BUT FAILED TO CONDUCT THE PROPER CALCULATION FOR THE PRODUCT LEFT IN HIS DELIVERY HOSE TO BE PURGED. AS THE DRIVER BLEW HIS HOSE DRY IT PUSHED THE CONTENTS INTO THE STORAGE TANK CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 21 GALLONS TO SPRAY OUT OF THE VENTILATION LINE AT THE TOP OF THE DOME. THE STORE OWNER WAS NOTIFIED BY THE ADJACENT BUSINESS THAT THEY HAD A STRONG SMELL OF BLEACH IN THEIR WAREHOUSE AND OFFICE. THE BLEACH THAT SPRAYED OUT OF THE STORAGE TANK FLOWED INTO THE WAREHOUSE CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE FLOOR, WALLS AND SOME MARINE PARTS. WE SENT AN OUTSIDE CONTACTOR TO MITIGATE THE EFFECTS OF THIS SPILL.

One portable metal tote of pro 829281552 had liquid under it when unloading trailer 311-1461 was started. After trying to find out where the liquid was coming from, it was determined that it was coming from the neck area of the valve assembly. Also during this investigation, three rags were found around the neck area of tote, all three rags were soaked from the material that was inside the tote. By looking at the neck area of valve, the liquid was leaking out from around the neck area that had some kind of putty material around it. When it was determined where the  leak was, the emergency number shown on the bill was called to report the incident, and then call was placed to safety manager, SM to inform him what was going on. The next call was to ERTS, to line up outside vendor to come in and clean up, and transfer contents of leaking tote to a good tote. Not sure how long the tote had been leaking.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JOB #33018: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF A RELEASE IN A TRAILER ON MONDAY, 10/01/2012 AT 0322 HOURS (CST). LAKEVILLE MOTOR EXPRESS HAD DISCOVERED THE RELEASE AT APPROXIMATELY 0100 HOURS. LAKEVILLE MOTOR EXPRESS INFORMED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT THAT THE RELEASE WAS FROM A 330-GALLON TOTE TANK CONTAINING A SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION 30% (LIQUID). THE RELEASE HAD IMPACTED THE TRAILER FLOOR, THE PARKING LOT, LOADING DOCK AND HAD ALSO IMPACTED A STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN. ENVIRONMENTAL  MANAGEMENT MOBILIZED ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION, LLC (SUBCONTRACTOR) TO RESPOND TO THE RELEASE. ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION ARRIVED ON SITE. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE TOTE TANK WAS IN A HARD-PLASTIC OUTER CONTAINER. THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM AN UNKNOWN LOCATION ON THE BOTTOM OF THE INNER TOTE TANK. THE PRODUCT IN THE LEAKING TOTE TANK WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TOTE TANK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION THEN BEGAN CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS OF THE IMPACTED AREAS. ABSORBENTS WERE APPLIED TO THE IMPACTED AREAS TO RECOVER THE FREE LIQUIDS. THE IMPACTED ABSORBENTS WERE RECOVERED AND PLACED INTO TWO (2) 55-GALLON DRUMS. ABSORBENT BOOM WAS PLACED IN THE STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN AND WOULD BE LEFT IN PLACE UNTIL A RAIN EVENT TO ENSURE ANY  REMAINING RESIDUE IS RECOVERED. THE TRAILER FLOOR, PARKING LOT AND THE LOADING DOCK AREA WERE THEN DECONTAMINATED UTILIZING VINEGAR. AFTER CLEANING ALL SURFACES WITH VINEGAR, THE AREAS WERE TESTED FOR PH. ALL PH READINGS FOR THE AREAS WERE NEUTRAL. ON 10/09/2012 ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION RETURNED TO THE SITE AND REMOVED THE ABSORBENT BOOM FROM THE STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN AND PLACED THE BOOM INTO A 30-GALLON DRUM.  ALL DRUMMED WASTE WAS STAGED ON SITE PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS TO BE MADE BY LAKEVILLE MOTOR EXDPRESS. DUE TO THE DAMAGED TOTE TANK BEING INSIDE OF THE OUT PACKAGING, IT COULD NOT BE DTERMINED AS TO THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE OR HOW THE INNER CONTAINER FAILED. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE DAMAGED CONTAINER SHIPPED BACK TO THE SHIPPER. THE SHIPPER IS TO INSPECT THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND DETERMINE THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.
column169: Our company will make every effort to prevent any future incidents like this from happening in the future. We recently formed a hazardous materials team of qualified instructors who will provide training that's in addition to what's already in place. All dockworkers and drivers will be retrained on the proper handling of hazardous materials, the proper procedures to follow in the case of an emergency and the need to be aware of their surroundings. Our facility is closed Saturday afternoon through Sunday when this incident began. We do, however, have regional drivers that arrive throughout the weekend and will be sending out notifications to them to perform yard checks of the facility and to alert us of any leaks or spills. We are working closely with the shipper to determine what caused the tote to leak. We value life and the safety of all and will do our best to insure this doesn't happen again.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, vehicle rollover resulted in the loss of approximately 5,200 gallons of diesel fuel from the cargo tanker.  The free product released to the soils adjacent to the roadway.  Live Oak Sheriff’s Department, Local Fire Department, and local responders were dispatched to assess the site.  The diesel fuel released to the soils adjacent to the roadside.  There was no impact to waterways or threat to enter state waters.  MidState Environmental was contracted to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, MidState Environmental used a vacuum truck to recover the free liquid, and secured the site, pending excavation of impacted soils.  MidState Environmental returned to excavate impacted soils, pull confirmation samples, and restore site to preexisting condition.  Environmental consultant was also hired to oversee response actions and site closure.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the release.

column168: ON WEDNESDAY OCTOBER 3RD, 2012 AT AROUND 1100 HRS, PROPANE BEGAN LEAKING FROM AN O-RING SEAL IN A 2" SWIVEL JOINT IN THE PROPANE TRUCK LOADING SYSTEM.  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS ISOLATED AFTER - 1 HOUR 50 MINUTES.    THE LEAK OCCURRED AFTER A PROPANE TRUCK WAS LOADED AND ISOLATION VALVES BETWEEN THE TRUCK AND LOADING RACK WERE CLOSED IN ACCORDANCE WITH FACILITY PROCEDURES.    SUBSEQUENT ANALYSIS INDICATES THAT THE SWIVEL JOINT O-RING FAILED. THE PROPANE SOURCE FOR THE ONGOING LEAK WAS THE TRUCK LIQUID FILL VALVE WHICH FAILED TO SEAT PROPERLY AFTER LOADING WAS COMPLETE.    AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE DRILL WAS TAKING PLACE IN THE REFINERY AT THE TIME OF THE LEAK. TWO CREWS OF THE PORT READING FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ON SITE. AS A CONSEQUENCE THEY PARTICIPATED IN THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE.    THE AREA WAS DELUGED WITH FIRE WATER TO SUPPRESS THE PROPANE VAPORS. A MEMBER OF THE HESS EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM EQUIPPED WITH SCBA AND BUNKER GEAR RESEATED THE TRUCK FILL VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED.
column169: THE FOUR SWIVEL JOINTS IN THE LOADING SYSTEM WERE REPLACED. FURTHER IMPROVEMENTS TO THE LOADING SYSTEM ARE UNDER REVIEW. A DISCUSSION WITH THE PROPANE CARRIER HAS BEEN HELD TO ENSURE THE TRUCK VALVE ON THE PROPANE TRANSPORTATION VEHICLE IS EVALUATED.

column168: ON OCTOBER 12TH, 2012, SCOTT OGLE AND RICK JONES WERE JUST STARTING OPERATIONS. THE FIRST MOVE OF THE DAY INVOLVED SHOVING THE OUTBOUND CONSIST ONTO TRACK 3 FOR NS TO PICK UP. THE CONSIST CONSISTED, IN THE ORDER IT WAS BEING SHOVED, OF THREE EMPTY COILED STEEL CARS, AN EMPTY TBOX CAR, AND SEVERAL LOADED SCRAP CARS.    THE LEAD WHEEL ON DJJX 30477 (FIRST LOADED SCRAP CAR) PICKED THE POINT ON THE 3-5 SWITCH AND TOOK THE LEAD TRUCK DOWN THE #5 TRACK. ESTIMATED TRAIN SPEED WAS APP. 3 MPH. MR. JONES FELT A JERK IN THE CONSIST, LOOKED BACK AND RECOGNIZED THE ISSUE, AND INSTRUCTED MR. OGLE OVER THE RADIO TO "SHOOT THE AIR'. THE TRAIN WAS UNABLE TO STOP BEFORE THE TBOX STRUCK A CUT OF LOADED ETHANOL CARS ON TRACK 5, INCLUDING SHPX 208417, WHICH ROLLED OVER AND STARTED A SLOW LEAK FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. BUCKETS WERE PLACED UNDER THE DRIP WITHIN 20 MINUTES AND FOR THE NEXT 12 HOURS UNTIL THE CAR WAS RIGHTED A TOTAL OF 18 GALLONS WAS COLLECTED. AMOUNT NOT CONTAINED WAS LESS THAN A GALLON.    TOTAL CARS DERAILED IN THE CONSIST WERE UTLX 204653 (NOT DERAILED BUT THE DAMAGED COUPLER AND DRAFT GEAR), SHPX 208417. CR 62938, TBOX 666366, UTLX 203420, DJJX 30477, AND DJJX 30340.
column169: THE SWITCH WAS COINCIDENTALLY INSPECTED ON 10.11.2012 AND NO EXCEPTIONS TAKEN. AFTER THE DERAILMENT THERE WAS NO CLEAR DEFINABLE CAUSE ATTRIBUTABLE TO THE WHEEL OR THE CAR. ONE OBSERVATION WAS THAT THE SWITCHPOINT IN QUESTION "MIGHT BE A LITTLE THICK."    THE DERAILMENT DAMAGE WAS REPAIRED AND THE SWITCH ADJUSTED TO RECOMMENDED TOLERANCES. A DIFFERENT CAR PICKED THE SAME SWITCHPOINT ON 10.29.2012 WITHOUT HAZMAT RELEASE. A SUBSEQUENT RECORDS SEARCH DEMONSTRATED THAT THE SWITCHPOINT HAD BEEN WELDED UP IN FIRST WEEK OF OCTOBER.    THE DAMAGE HAS BEEN REPAIRED, THE SUSPECT SWITCHPOINT REPLACED AND SUPPLEMENTAL WITH A SWITCHPOINT GUARD, AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SWITCH AGAIN ADJUSTED TO RECOMMENDED TOLERANCES.

column168: Tank car PROX 40968 in the railyard was reporting leaking product from its top fitting area which was evaporating. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected PROX 40968 and determined that the closed liquid valve was leaking from its loose closure plug. The responder tool tightened the loose closure plug which significantly slowed the product release. A follow-up inspection by contract responders discovered that the liquid valve's 3 inch ball valve was not seating properly due to Teflon tape debris caught between the ball valve and the valve's gasket seat. The responders depressured PROX 40968 and removed the debris. Afterwards, no further product seepage was observed after the responders restored the 15 psi nitrogen blanket within PROX 40968. All other valves and fittings inspected were found secure. Intact shipper seal (0004651) at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal SRS000248.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: ON 10/18/12 A SHIPMENT WAS IDENTIFIED AS CONTAINING DRY ICE AT THE DHL CVG GATEWAY LOCATED AT 236 WENDELL H FORD BLVD, ERLANGER, KY 41018. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF A PLASTIC COOLER WITH A SNAP ON LID CONTAINING A STYROFOAM COOLER WITH LID. THE INNER STYROFOAM COOLER CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 3 KGS OF DRY ICE THAT WAS COOLING A COMMODITY IDENTIFIED AS A SERUM (RABIES ANTIBODY TITER). TRACKING INDICATES TRANSPORTATION BY AIR.

On 10/24/12 at 1400, the TRANSFLO-Charlotte General Products terminal manger  discovered that tank car DOWX 73008 was leaking slightly from the bottom valve. Approximately 2 ounces of  2-Ethyl Hexyl Acrylate leaked into the rock ballast and evaporated. A catch pan was placed under the railcar to catch additional leaks.  No tank car to cargo tank transfers had been taken out of this tank car. A tank car arrival inspection had been conducted with 24 hours and no leak was discovered that time. No unloading connections had been attached and no valves were operated. The shipper (DOW) was notified and contacted RESCAR to coordinate repairs. Less than a liquid ounce of 2-Ethyl Hexyl Acrylate was collected in the catch pan between 10/24/2012 and 11/2/2012.    RESCAR technicians arrived at the terminal on 11/2/2012 to attempt to repair tank car and stop the leak. They made contact with DOW and were told to attempt to tighten the bolts on the bottom flange to stop the leak. Only two of the eight bolts even moved slightly. The RESCAR crew re-inspected the tank car about 90 minutes later and could still see moisture around the gasket. No drips have been witnessed or product seen in the drain pan in over a week. No railcar switches on Track 9 will be conducted until advised to do so. Exact cause of leaking flange is unknown.
column169: Root Cause: Possible leak or damage to the flange gasket.     Corrective Actions:  1. Notify railcar shipper of leaking railcar.- COMPLETED- 10/24/2012  2. Work with RESCAR to attempt repairs on-site.- COMPLETED-11/2/2012  3. Unload railcar and wait for a One-Time Movement Approval (OTMA) from the shipper before releasing railcar for required repairs.- OPEN

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, THE STORAGE TANK OVERPRESSURIZED WHICH CAUSED THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE DELIVERY FITTING AND THE TANK TO BECOME COMPROMISED. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE CONCRETE/ASPHALT PARKING SURFACE AND WAS REMEDIATED BY KENAN PERSONNEL WITHOUT INCIDENT. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: THE VENTING ISSUES WITH THE STORAGE TANK WERE BROUGHT TO THE ATTENTION OF THE CUSTOMER AND THE NECESSARY REPAIRS ARE TO BE MADE.

column17: Kinder Morgan c/o Norfolk Southern-Thoroughbred Bulk Terminal-Roanoke
column168: On 10/24/12 at 8:20 A.M., ethanol transloading pump #1 started leaking ethanol from the lid of the pump's strainer basket. The transload pump operator immediately shut the pump down and reported the release to the terminal manager. There was an estimated two liquid ounces of ethanol that was released onto the asphalt from the leaking strainer basket. Oil absorbents were placed over the release and swept up. The investigation revealed that the O-ring of the filter lid was mis-aligned and did not properly fit when lid was closed. The O-ring on the lid was re-adjusted and the lid was tightened to stop the leak. The O-ring was then replaced to prevent re-occurrence. No stormwater drains were impacted by the ethanol release.  Notifications were made to the Chief dispatcher of Norfolk Southern, the terminal owner.
column169: Roanoke transloading pump operators were re-trained to inspect O-rings more closely before closing the filter lid. Any warped, worn, or damaged O-rings will be immediately replaced. Spill pans will be placed under the filters for the first transfers after the O-rings are replaced or re-aligned as a precautionary measure to capture potential leaks.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Broken Component or Device
column168: UTLX 662319 was observed with product on the side of the tank car while it was being taken to a customer on Saturday, October 20, 2012 at approximately 730 hrs. It was determined that this was not an active leak, product would splash on the sides of the tank when being switched in the yard, so the car was returned to the American Yard. The car was placed in bad order hold status pending contact with the shipper. On 10/26 the shipper authorized repairs and remediation to be performed by M&M Protection. Once authorized the car was moved to the repair track. M&M responded on 10/29 and discovered that the manway gasket was cracked/brokemn. They installed a new gasket and sealed the tank car. They also found a defective o-ring on the vacuum relief valve and replaced the o-ring. After making the repairs that car was pressure washed with a biodegradeable solvent and released from bad order status.
column169: The shipper was notified of the issue and is investigating the cause of the defective manway gasket and VRV o-ring failure.

column25: UPS Freight for Kemira Chemicals Inc.
column168: Intermodal trailer FSTZ 813860 that arrived on an inbound BNSF train was reported leaking an unknown liquid substance. FSTZ 813860 was removed from its rail flatcar it was riding upon and carefully taken to the facility's containment area dock. Contract responders reported finding one 275 gallon poly IBC that had leaked after a palletized load stacked atop this IBC shifted and came to rest directly on the rigid inner receptacle between the outer metal caging cross pieces. The weight of the palletized lading partially crushed and cracked the inner receptacle releasing product within. The remaining product in this IBC was transferred into another suitable IBC. Interior and exterior spillage on FSTZ 813860 and the railcar was cleaned with a hot water/detergent solution. Spent cleaning liquid was vacuumed and along with other cleaning materials were all earmarked for appropriate disposal. All lading was returned into the cleaned FSTZ 813860 for furtherance.
column169: Ensure intermodal shipments have the appropriate interior blocking and bracing to prevent in-transit lading shifts.

column168: V1 (Pilot Flying J) was driving Northbound on I-95 just before the Tydings Bridge, when he observed V2 (a Ford Explorer) hit the median and spin 90 degrees, then crossing both lanes of traffic and strike the cab of V1. V1 stated that this impact caused V1 to run into the guard rail and then flip over the guardrail. V1 stated that both the truck and trailer rolled completely over, landing in the ditch along side I-95 Northbound at Mile Marker 90.3 just before theTydings Bridge. V1 contacted the Pilot Flying J management team, as well as the first responders that came to the scene for mediation. Pilot Flying J then contacted their third party clean up contractor to survey and then clean the affected areas. V1's trailer sustained damage to the front compartment, which resulted in 3,200 gallons of Diesel Fuel being spilled.
column169: All Pilot Flying J drivers receive safety training, which teaches them to always be alert and defensive when driving. After reviewing the details of the event, it appears that it was not a lack of driver ability/awareness that lead to this taking place. Pilot Flying J will however continue to train our drivers in all areas of safety.

column168: When the driver arrived at the tankwash to pick up a loaded cargo tank that was being relayed, he noticed a slow drip coming from the barrel in front of the rear tandem.  He immediately put a bucket under it to contain the leakage.  We weren't sure if there was an issue with the barrel or if something got in the insulation of the trailer and was leaking out.  To err on the side of safety, the product was transferred to another trailer when one became available later in the day. Approximately 3 gallons of product had leaked out before the transfer successfully took place in the tankwash bay with an emergency response crew standing by.

column168: On October 18, 2012, at 1215 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Stanley Yard, Walbridge, OH, noticed product underneath the bottom hopper compartment of NAHX 508645, a loaded covered hopper of UN1942, Ammonium Nitrate. The hopper car was isolated. The shipper, Orica Canada Inc., was notified via Chemtrec, report #2012-10-18-00117. SWS Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Stanley Yard. SWS met with the CSXT Mechanical Department and found the hopper bottom slide gate closure partially opened. The hopper slide gate was properly secured, all spilled material was removed from the tracks and drummed for disposal. The shipper representative, Paul Kaupas, was notified of the situation found. The product release was secured and NAHX 508645 was released for disposition.  This incident did not require a special move.    NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(3+0) = 90  Cause code: 662
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On October 17, 2012, at 1458 hour, an FRA Inspector in the CSXT Hawthorne yard discovered GATX 8120, a loaded sulfuric acid tank car, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Southern States, was notified via CHEMTREC report #2012-10-17-00195. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 1 of 4 liquid valve flange bolts less than tool tight and the frangible disc blown. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, John Fogarity, 912-232-1101. Contractor personnel secured the flange bolt, replaced the frangible disc and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI: 5(5+5+0)X(2+0) = 100  Cause Code: 284/441
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On October 25, 2012, at 0745 hours, personnel in the CSXT Bennett Yard discovered   TAZX 260005, a loaded tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Giant Resource Recovery, was notified via Chemtrec report number 2012-10-25-00035. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and determined the cause of the release was due to a misaligned vacuum relief valve o-ring.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Giant Resource Recovery representative Sammy Prescott at 803-938-2937. Contractor personnel repositioned the o-ring and decontaminated the exterior of the container.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI = 5 (5+3+1) x (2+0) = 90  Cause Code: 457
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On October 30, 2012, at 2200 hours, a switching crew at the CSXT Niagara Yard noticed vapors and smelled an odor from HOKX 8338, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, coming from around the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and Trainmaster contacted the consignee. NYS-DEC and CHEMTREC report 2012-10-31-00144, were notified. Occident personnel responded to the yard, Mr. Robert Waz, (716-278-7777)  found #1 fill hole swing bolt less than tool tight. The swing bolt was tightened and the vapor release was secured. HOKX 8338 was release for disposition and transport.    This incident DID require a special switching move.    NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100  Cause Code: 224
column169: No additional comments.

column168: THE PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON HWY 35 IN ARDMORE, OKLAHOMA WHEN SHE LOST CONTROL AND WENT OFF THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED. APPROXIMATELY 1700 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER. P&D ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE DRIVING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: THE DISTTECH, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER ULTRAZOL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. THIS WAS A BRAND NEW STORAGE TANK THAT WAS JUST INSTALLED. THE COMPANY THAT INSTALLED THE TANK FAILED TO REMOVE A PLUG AFTER PERFORMING A PRESSURE TEST. AS A RESULT, PRESSURE IN THE TANK BUILT UP AND WHEN THE DRIVER UNHOOKED HIS HOSE AFTER MAKING THE DELIVERY APPROXIMATELY 400 GALLONS OF ULTRAZOL WAS RELEASED. THE DRIVER WAS SPRAYED IN THE EYE WITH THE ULTRAZOL AND SOUGHT TREATMENT AT A LOCAL EMERGENCY ROOM. HE WAS DIAGNOSED WITH CHEMICAL CONJUNCTIVITIS AND RELEASED. THE SPILL CLEAN-UP WAS HANDLED BY THE CUSTOMER.
column169: THE PROPER MODIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE STORAGE TANK TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE.

column168: On Monday October 22, 2012 Orica driver, Jerry Lee Lewis was involved in a single vehicle accident on I-85 North near Archdale, North Carolina while en route to a customer location driving MMU unit 06039. At approximately 6:47am Mr. Lewis failed to maintain control of the MMU causing the vehicle to leave the road, striking a guardrail and overturning down an embankment, coming to rest against a tree. The MMU was loaded with approximately 22,000LBS of Oxidizer emulsion (UN3139),  90 1.1 B Detonators (UN0030) and 90 1.1D Boosters (UN0042). No emulsion was spilled from the tank and a small amount leaked from the broken line (Less than 1 Gallon). Both Dets and Boosters remained secured in their IME-22 magazines undamaged. A small amount of diesel fuel, engine oil, and antifreeze leaked from the vehicle and Hepaco, LLC, an Orica third party environmental Response Company cleaned incident scene. The cleanup and disposal process completed to state and federal standards.    The cargo tanks did not fail or receive damage that would require repair prior to further use - the tanks are skinned and that did recieve significant damage.  The tanks have ribbs that provide protection to the lading retention - some of the these ribs sustained damage that would require repair prior to further use.  These tanks will be put out of service
column169: The cause of the incident is being investigated by a 3rd party accident reconstruction firm.      The packages held containment and worked well.    If the invistigation indicates further training is required - it will be provided to drivers.

column168: Impact between Vehicle 1 and Vehicle 2. Vehicle 1 jerked right impacting guardrail. Vehicle 1 jerks back left and overturns. Vehicle 1 slides EB on its side pushing Vehicle 2. Vehicle 1 tank trailer exploded and burned Vehicle 1and tank trailer to frame. Vehicle 2 that came to rest in front of Vehicle 1 also caught fire and burned. Shell of Vehicle 2 seemed to be intact. Driver of Vehicle 1 trapped inside and burned beyond recognition. Driver of Vehicle 2 escaped with no injuries. Emergency Responders arrived on scene immediately and began to control fire and accident scene. Responding to scene were local Fire/EMS Units, BEST Environmental, IDOE Management, Interstate Towing Service, Indiana EPA, Shelby County Coroner, Shelby County Sheriff Department, Officer Crawford, 1st Sergeant Tyler Utterback, Trooper William Gannon, IN Department of Highways and others not known. Most product was burned up in fire. Foam from response efforts was dug up. Roadway where Vehicle 1 and tank Trailer burned was dug up and replaced. Still awaiting descriptive reports from BEST Environmental on what actions were taken and those still ongoing operations to remediate area.
column169: We are not sure what happened to cause this tragic incident. We are highly aware of the hazards present when transporting hazardous materials. Our Safety Department instructs our drivers to handle emergency situations training them on speed management, physical properties of hazardous materials handled and being transported, Equipment safety features and design and what physically happens in rollover situations. We feel our driver did everything he could do in that situation to keep it on the road and away from the other motorists losing his life in the process. We will continue training our drivers in such a manner using tragic incidents such as this one to learn from.

column168: On October 29, 2012, Vitran Express contacted ERTS in regards to the reference release.  Vitran Express advised that the release was due to a faulty valve on the tote.  ERTS dispatched Terra Contracting to the site to perform remediation activities.  Terra personnel estimated that approximately 200 gallons of material was released due to the incident.

On October 30, 2012, A&D Environmental Services contacted ERTS in regards to the referenced incident.  ERTS dispatched ES&H to the site to perform the necessary cleanup activities.  ES&H personnel arrived on site and performed the necessary cleanup activities.  It was noted that the drum appeared to be leaking from the bottom of the drum which appeared to be deteriorating resulting in the release.

AFTER HOOKING TO LOADED TRAILER AT THE GENERATOR SITE, HAZMAT DRIVER FAILED TO ENSURE THAT THE 3" WASHOUT CAP ON TOP OF OUR TANKER WAS PROPERLY SECURED, WHICH IS THE OPENING WHERE GENERATOR LOADS THROUGH.   UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INCINERATOR AT THE TSDF, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT MATERIAL WAS DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TRAILER AND A SMALL AMOUNT UNDER THE TRAILER ON THE GROUND, WHICH HAD ESCAPED OUTSIDE THE CRASH BOX.  UPON FURTHER OBSERVATION, MATERIAL WAS NOTICED ON THE PAVEMENT BY THE GUARD SHACK AND A TRAIL LEADING UP TO IT FROM THE ENTRANCE WAY. MATERIAL HAD DRIED AT THIS POINT. MATERIAL ON ROUTES OUTSIDE TSDF PROPERTY WERE ALSO NOTED.
column169: Fleet message was sent out via satellite communication to all drivers reminding/instructing them to ensure all openings are secure before moving any trailer. The topic of tank closures and this incident will be incorporated into HazMat Environmental Group's annual DOT/OSHA training. It was also emphasized to the generator that they check all closures of valves and fittings when filling activities are complete.

column168: Reliance Propane delivery driver Chris Wilson had finished loading a bobtail delivery truck.  He had stowed the loading hoses, secured them with a chain and padlock, and locked the chain link gate surrounding the storage tank.  He had not yet installed the caps on the loading connections, and for some reason, opened the manual ball valve at the loading connection, draining about 2ft. of 2" pipe up to the next automatic shut-off valve. Some of the gas released ignited, causing his burn injury.  The release lasted for a second or two, and stopped as that section of piping emptied.  There was no additional release or fire.  There was no equipment malfunction or damage.  Truck and Storage tank were inspected by an outside industry inspector, and returned to service.
column169: We have been unable to determine why the driver opened the valve.  He has properly completed this task hundreds of times.  We have reviewed the incident with fellow employees, and the need to avoid operator complacency or in-attention, although training had been adequate to properly complete the task.  We will be re-fitting a newly released loading valve design which will further limit the amount of product that could be released.  We are also installing cameras on our trucks and at storage locations to further monitor the truck loading process.

column168: Our driver picked up a pre-loaded and sealed CTMV from the shipper location. Our driver performed his pre-trip inspection and left the shipper yard. When our driver arrived at a truck stop in MS, he again inspected the trailer and found product on the top of the CTMV exterior, near the front washout. Our driver observed product extending about 12 inches from the cleanout, and saw no evidence that spilled product dripped off of the CTMV or onto the ground. Our driver inspected the washout cap and found it was loose. He removed the cap and replaced the gasket as a precautionary measure. He installed the cap and tightened it with a tool. Our driver carries a spill kit that includes absorbent towels. Our driver cleaned the product from the CTMV and put the used towels in his containment bag. He took the used towels to commercial tank wash for proper disposal. Our Event 35184.

column168: DRIVER (DSR) DROPPED A TRAILER IN CON-WAY FREIGHT (CWF) YARD. CWF TRAILER DAMAGE - PASSENGER SIDE LANDING GEAR LEG BENT. NO INJURIES. DSR BACKED UNDER THE TRAILER, HEARD IT LATCH, DID A TUG TEST, WENT DOWN THE D/S THEN WENT UP THE P/S LOOKING AT EVERYTHING AND PICK UP THE WHEEL CHOCK, CONNECTED THE AIR LINES, CHECKED THE 5TH WHEEL FOR NO GAPS, LOOKED AT THE PIN UNDER THE TRAILER AND RELEASE ARM WAS IN. DSR STATED PULLED OUT THEN SWUNG OUT TO THE LEFT FROM THE PARKING SPACE TO GO DOWN A FEW TRAILERS FOR THE REAR. DSR WAS SWINGING BACK TO THE RIGHT WHEN THE TRAILER DROPPED. DSR STATED HE STOPPED AS SOON AS THE TRAILER DROPPED (AIR LINES STAYED CONNECTED). DSR STATED THE RELEASE ARM WAS IN BUT THE JAW WAS OPEN WHEN HE LOOKED AT THE 5TH WHEEL AFTER THE TRAILER HAD DROPPED.    WHILE REMOVING THE FREIGHT AFTER THE TRAILER DROPPED, SUPERVISOR NOTICED A BAG OF A TOXIC SOLID LEAKING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. THE SHIPMENT WSA LOADED FROM THE MIDDLE TO THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO CWF SAFETY DEPT. AT APPROX. 21:13 EASTERN. SAFETY DEPT CONTACTED ERTS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATION VENDOR TO ASSIST WITH CLEAN-UP FROM 1 BAG WHICH SPILLED. ERTS REPORTED RELEASE TO TEMA (#2093) AND NRC. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR COMPLETED CLEAN-UP BY 12:43 EST, 10/06/2012.                                                 CORRECTIVE ACTION FINAL REPORT CREATED BY ERTS STATES THE FAILURE OCCURRED IN THE BODY (104), BEING PUNCTURED (309), IMPACTED W/SHARP OR PROTRUDING OBJECT (516).  AMOUNT RELEASED DOCUMENTED IN ERTS INCIDENT RESPONSE FORM, POST-ASSESSMENT.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE STAGED AT THE GLENERY, INC. FACILITY, TRAILER WAS FLOODED AS A RESULT OF A HURRICANE. AS A RESULT, ONE (1) 2000 LB BAG OF PRODUCT WAS DAMAGED. THE CONTENTS OF THE BAG WERE RELEASED INSIDE THE TRAILER, WITH A MINIMAL AMOUNT TO THE GROUND SURFACE BENEATH TRAILER. QUALIFIED SPILL RESPONSE OF KENILWORTH, NEW JERSEY WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. HUDSON COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. QUALIFIED SPILL RESPONSE OFFLOADED THE TRAILER, DECONNED, AND NEUTRALIZED AFFECTED AREAS. THE DIRT/SOIL BENEATH TRAILER WAS EXCAVATED AND PLACED INTO ROLL-OFF BOXES, ALONG WITH CONTAINMENT FREIGHT. ALL FREE PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AND CONTAINERIZED, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO STATE WATERS AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: As the incident occurred due to a natural disaster, no plans are currently in place to prevent recurrence. However, Glenery, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: THE ACCIDENT INVOLVED 11 SEMI TRUCKS AND TRAILERS AND ONE PASSENGER VEHICLE. THE WEATHER WAS FOGGY AND IT WAS SNOWING. VISBILITY WAS POOR AS THE SUN WAS RISING IN THE EAST AND IT WAS BARELY LIGHT AT THE TIME. THE ACCIDENT WAS A CHAIN REACTION WHEN A PLYCOM TRUCK SLOWED IN FRONT OF A DART TRUCK. SEVERAL TRACTOR TRAILERS THEN COLLIDED.  THE MELTON TRUCK WAS HIT FROM BEHING BY A WERNER TRUCK THAT HAD BEEN HIT BY A FIRST FLEET TRUCK. THE WERNER TRUCK IGNITED ON IMPACT WITH THE MELTON TRUCK. THE WERNER AND MELTON TRUCKS AND TRAILERS WERE ENGULFED IN FLAMES AND WERE CONSUMED BY THE RESULTING FIRE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. THREE 5 GALLON CONTAINERS OF THE BONDING ADHESIVE ESCAPED THE FIRE. WE CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION TO COLLECT THE CONTAINERS FOR DISPOSAL. WE HAVE NOT YET RECEIVED THE DISPOSAL MANIFESTS. ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION COLLECTED 3 SOIL SAMPLES IN THE AREA WHERE THE RUNOFF FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT MIGRATED. THE SAMPLES WERE ANALYZED FOR VOCS USING METHOD SW 846. ALL CONSTITUENTS WERE NON DETECT. WE WILL UPDATE THIS REPORT WITH THE DISPOSAL MANIFEST ONCE RECEIVED FROM THE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR.
column169: THIS ACCIDENT AND THE FOLLOWING DAMAGES WERE OUT OF THE CONTROL OF MELTON TRUCK LINES.

Product was offloaded to another unit on site.  There was 17.2 bbls remaining in    the damaged trailer according to the gauge. Gary was transported    by his wife to Cheyenne, WY to complete a DOT drug and alcohol test at Compliance Admin Services.    Custom Environmental on site on 10/18/12 8am to perform clean up.  A release of 1 – 1.5 bbls on site.

column168: On 10/3/12, between 7:00-7:20 a.m. Illini FS Inc. employees Joe Graning & Ted Toliver were in the process of filling two 1,450 gallon anhydrous ammonia nurse tanks that were placed onto a single trailer. The dual 1,450 gallon nurse tanks were on the southeast side of the anhydrous ammonia riser. At the time of the incident Mr. Graning was making connections to the 1,45O gallon nurse tank stationed closest to the anhydrous ammonia riser. Also, during this time Danial Gaskin another Illini FS Inc employee was in the process of disconnecting dual 1,450 gallon nurse tanks place onto a single trailer from a truck on the west side of the anhydrous ammonia riser closest to the 30,000.•gallon anhydrous ammonia storage tank. Mr. Graning had just completed making the connection of the vapor host end valve at the riser to the liquid/vapor fill valve on the 1,450 gallon nurse tank. Just prior to Mr. Graning making the connections, Mr. Toliver had retrieved an acme gasket as Mr. Graning was having some difficulty making the connections. Mr. Graning informed Mr. Toliver that he was able to make the connection of the vapor hose end valve to the liquid/vapor fill valve on the 1,450 gallon nurse tank and the acme gasket that Mr. Toliver originally retrieved was not needed.    Mr.Granlng then proceeded to connect the liquid line hose end angle valve to the liquid/vapor fill valve on the 1,450.gallon nurse tank. Mr. Graning is unsure as to what happened next, as anhydrous ammonia released from the liquid line hose end angle valve. Mr. Graning stated he yelled "OH EXPLETIVE" & the next thing that he recalls was anydrous ammonia releasing from the end of the liquid line hose end angle valve. Mr. Gmning stated that possibly the valve hand wheel on the liquid line hose end angle valve turned in the open position, but is unsure of how it might have occurred. Mr. Toliver had his back to Mr. Graning facing north as he was putting the unused acme gasket back onto a wire storage hook. During the on-set of the release of anhydrous ammonia, Danial Gaskin avoided the release by heading west under the 30,000 & 18,000 gallon anhydrous ammonia storage tanks & ending north of the anhydrous .ammonia riser near the 150 gallon emergency water container.  Mr. Gaskin asked Mr. Toliver where Mr. Graning was, Mr. Toliver stated he was unsure as to the location of Mr. Graning. Mr. Gaskin instructed Mr. Toler to stay in the emergency water as he went to find Mr. Graning. Mr. Gaskin stated he found Mr. Graning between the anhydrous ammonia riser and the fuel storage tanks in the anhydrous ammonia vapor cloud. Mr. Gaskin went into the anhydrous ammonia vapor cloud and led Mr. Graning out of the vapor cloud & then guided Mr. Graning into the 150 gallon emergency water container that Mr. Toliver was currently in.    Mr. Gaskin then instructed Joe Cannon, an employee of Iilini FS Inc. to contact 911 & stop the leak from the liquid line hose end angle valve at the anhydrous ammonia riser. Pro- A
column169: WE PROVIDE ANNUAL TRAINING IN THE PROPER PROCEDURES FOR HANDLING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. WE ALSO POINT OUT AREAS TO PREVENT HUMAN ERROR SUCH AS HAPPENED IN THIS INSTANCE.

column168: AS DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO EXIT OFF THE INTERSTATE, ANOTHER DRIVER NOTIFIED HIM ON THE CB RADIO THAT HIS TRAILER APPEARED TO BE VENTING FUMES INTO THE AIR. DRIVER PULLED UP TO THE REAR OF THE PROPERTY, AT A TRUCK STOP, AWAY FROM OTHER TRUCKS. AFTER EXITING THE TRUCK HE NOTICED VAPORS COMING FROM A FLANGE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER. HE NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR, AND CALLS WERE MADE TO AUTHORITIES ALONG WITH A CALL TO A MECHANIC. OIL MOP WAS ALSO CALLED OUT, AS THEY ARE AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY. THERE WAS ESTIMATED 5-10 GALLONS ONTO THE GROUND, AND WAS CLEANED UP AND BE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THE FLANGE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, AND DRIVE CONTINUED ON TO HIS CUSTOMER.
column169: IMMEDIATE AWARENESS WAS BROUGHT TO THE SHOP WHERE LAST INSPECTION OF TRAILER WAS DONE. THEY WERE TOLD TO RE-CHECK THE TIGHTNESS OF ANY AND ALL BOLTS THAT WERE REMOVED OR REPLACED. IT APPEARS A COUPLE OF BOLTS MAY HAVE VIBRATED LOOSE AFTER LOADING BECAUSE THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF ANY VAPOR RELEASE WHEN IT WAS BEING LOADED, OR EN-ROUTE. LOAD TRAVELED OVER 200 MILES BEFORE IT WAS NOTICED TO BE RELEASING VAPORS IN THE AIR.

column168: SCHENKER, INC. (SCHNENKER) OFFICE LOCATED AT 3191 MIKE COLLINS DRIVE, EAGAN, MN WAS CONTACTED BY PAUL ANDERSON OF SINOVAST ELECTRONICS LTD HONG KONG (SINOVAST ELECTRONICS) TO HANDLE A SHIPMENT OF USED COMPUTER PARTS. THE CARGO WAS BEING SENT DIRECTLY TO THE STEAMSHIP LINE FROM ARROW SCRAP CORPORATION (ARROW SCRAP) LOCATED AT WHEATLEY HEIGHTS NY.    SCHNENKER RECEIVED THE DOCUMENTS FROM ARROW SCRAP AS SUPPLIER FOR SINOVAST ELECTRONICS TO MOVE THE SHIPMENT VIA OCEAN TO FU YANG AGENCY IN HONG KONG. ONCE SCHENKER RECEIVED THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS, IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED 1,855 LITHIUM ION BATTERIES. SCHENKER CONTACTED BOTH PAUL ANDERSON OF SINOVAST ELECTRONICS AND DON GALINDO OF ARROW SCRAP WITH CONCERNS THAT THIS SHIPMENT WOULD BE A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT AND REQUIRES A DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION WITH PROPER MARKING, LABELING AND PACKING AS INDICATED UNDER THE IMDG REGULATIONS. SCHENKER ADDITIONAL REQUESTED PROVISION, IF APPLICABLE.    PAUL ANDERSON CONTACTED SCHENKER ADVISING SCHENKER HE HAS SHIPPED THOUSANDS OF BATTERIES OVER THE YEARS AND THEY WERE NON-HAZARDOUS. WE WERE INFORMED BY DON GALINDO THAT THE 1,8555 LITHIUM ION BATTERIES WERE PACKED LOOSE IN A GAYLORD BOX.    SCHENKER CONTACTED THE STEAMSHIP LINE HAPAG LLOYD AND ADVISED THEM NOT TO LOAD THE SHIPMENT. SCHENKER CONTACTED PAUL ANDERSON OF SINOVAST ELECTRONICS ADVISING HIM WE WOULD NOT HANDLE THE SHIPMENT AND HE MUST MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE IT PICKED UP AND MOVED OUT OF THE STEAMSHIP LINE.
column169: SCHENKER INC., EMPLOYEES QUESTIONED THIS SHIPMENT AS A RESULT OF FOLLOWING THE DANGEROUS GOODS TRAINING RECEIVED WHICH IS PROVIDED IN IMDG, IATA AND 49 CFR REGULATIONS.

column168: OUR TRUCK TANKER WAS MAKING A GASOLINE DELIVERY AT THE STATION IN SUNNYVALE, CA ON OCT. 10, 2012 AT APPROXIMATELY 1945 HOURS. AS THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE GASOLINE FROM THE TANKER, ONE OF THE PNEUMATIC VALVE CLOSED BY ITSELF DUE TO LOSS OF AIR, DRIVER THROUGHT THAT THE TANKER IS EMPTY, BUT THERE WAS STILL SOME PRODUCT LEFT IN THE TANKER, DRIVER CLOSED THE DISCHARGE VALVE, DRIVER ALSO SHUT DOWN THE PNEUMATIC VALVE THAT IS NEXT TO DISCHARGE VALVE, BUT THE PNEUMATIC VALVE DID NOT SHUT DOWN TO THE END, IT WAS IN MIDDLE OF OPENING AND CLOSE, AS THE TRUCK LEAVES THE STATION, AIR PRESSURE START BUILDING UP IN TANKER AIR RESERVE TANK, THIS TANK OPERATES THE PNEUMATIC VALVE, IT CAUSE THE PNEUMATIC VALVE TO OPEN.
column169: WE REPLACE THE PNUEMATIC DISCHARGE VALVE SWITCH AND FIX A SLOW LEAK THAT CAUSE A LOSS OF AIR IN TANKER AIR TANK THAT CONTROLS THE PNUEMATIC VALVE.

column169: TRAVELING THE RURAL ROUTES IN AGRICULTRAL AREAS REQUIRE AS MUCH ATTENTION AS THE MAIN INTERSTATE SYSTEM. WE TRAIN OUR DRIVER'S TO CONSTANTLY BE AWARE OF THEIR SURROUNDINGS AND WHEN APPROACHING SLOWER TRAFFIC TO TAKE EXTRA PRECAUTIONS SUCH AS FOLLOWING DISTANCES AND CLEAR PASSING LANES. WE WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN OUR DRIVER'S IN THIS MANNER USING THIS PARTICULAR INCIDENT AS A TEACHING OPPORTUNITY.    THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT HAS ALWAYS FELT THAT MORE TRAINING SHOULD BE DONE CONCERNING LARGE VEHICLE AWARENESS ON A LOCAL LEVEL WHEN PERSONS APPLY FOR OR RENEW A DRIVERS LICENSE. ENLIST THE HELP OF TRUCKING COMPANIES AND INSURANCE AGENCIES (ONES THAT PROVIDE TRUCKING INSURANCE) ON A LOCAL LEVEL TO ACHIEVE THE TRAINING.

column168: The vehicle involved in this incident was a 3000 gallon, 3 compartment truck mounted tank, with dual pumps, hosereels and meters.  Each compartment had a capacity of 1000 gallons.  The front compartment contained 700 gallons of diesel fuel, compartment 3 contained 650 gallons of diesel fuel and compartment 3 was empty.  The truck was heading northbound of I29 and just north of exit 73 out driver heard a loud band under the truck.  He  looked in his mirrors and saw something laying on the road.  He then looked ahead to check traffic so that he could get to the side of the road, stopped and exited the truck which was quickly engulfed in flames.  911 was called and the SD Hwy Patrol, Tea Police and Fire departments from both Sioux Falls and Tea responded along with the SDDOT Hwy Dept.  Northboud traffic had already stopped and once responders arrived the northbound traffic was detoured.  Once the fire was extinguished and the remains of the truck cooled down, it was determined that compartment 1 which had contained 700 gallons of diesel fuel was empty. Compartment 2, which still contained fuel had a small leak on the emergency valve on the bottom of the tank.  The leak was contained with absorbent socks and pads until another of out trucks arrived to pump the fuel out of the compartment.  We also pumped the fuel out of the engin fuel tanks, which were not leading, to prevent another release.  While we were pumping the fuel the Hwy Department cleaned up the inside lane, set up the inside lane, set up cones and opened one nortbound lane to taffic.  As to what caused the release and fire, first responders found a U-joint with the slip joint attached at the start of the fuel stain on the pavement.  They also found a 2 inch Victualic pipe connecting clamp and part of an emergency valve a short distance away.  Looking at the truck, when we got it back to out facility, we found taht the driveshaft between the hanger bearing and the first differential had come off.  One of the U-joint cup clamps was still in place but the other one was missing.  One boldt that holds that clamp in place was missing and the other bolt was broken off.  We are assuming that the missing bolt came loose and vibrated out, putting excessive stress on the remaining bolt until it failed causing the driveshaft to drop down and swing aroung wildly under the truck.  the shaft hit the emergency valve and broke the casting, damaging it so severely that it leakedit also appeared to have hit the 2 inch pipe that runs from the gasoline pump under the truck to the meter at the rear of the truck, breaking the victaulic clamp and causing the gasoline residue in the line to ignite and this in turn caused the leaking diesel fuel to ignite.  Most of the diesel burned up as it leaded from the truck.  The report we have from out environmental consultant states that we will have to remove some topsoil and replace it with clean soil and seed it. column168: See Attachment:Our TSU driver attempted to make a delivery at Luli Pool at 5:30 AM on 10/16/12. He found the 1900 tank with 25 gallons inside and began to make his connections. This location has a concrete wall around the tank he is filling. Jose started the unload process and after a while noticed that there was an unusually strong smell of bleach coming from the area. As he went walking back to the tank location he noticed that the tank had just over 800 gallons in it but immediately noticed that there was bleach coming from under the door of the fill room, so he ran back to the tanker and closed all his valves. The driver ran back through the alley to the tank, climbed up on the fence and noticed that the main valve and the valve coming out of the containment were both left open. He climb to the top of the fence and lay his body across it, and was able to close the outside valve.    It was later discovered by Jaimie Johnson (AUC Miami Branch Manager) when the owner of Luli Pool arrived onsite and opened the fill room that the leak was due to a broken pipe approx 3 feet downstream of the valve outside of the containment. The pipe had a folded pool liner laid across it and footprints as if it had been used as a stepping point to gain access to the tank. This appears to be the cause of the broken pipe and there is no way that the driver could have seen this from outside the fill area.    Cliff Berry (Chemical Cleanup Company) was called to the scene to handle the recovery of the bleach, but by the time they arrived all the product was either down the drain in the parking lot or absorbed into the pervious soil next to the tank.  NRC was contacted and a report was made # 10257414.  After completing the investigation and concluding that this was not the drivers fault but the customers, NRC was again contacted by the VP of Operations and was told that a reversal NRC report would be made under # 1027436.
column169: The owner of the pool company mentioned that they had been victims of a robbery 2 nights prior to this  event. He stated that the robbers gained access to their tank and fill-room and were able to drain the  tank completely dry (claiming 1300 gallons lost to theft). Though the pipe could have been broken during  the robbery as it appears to have been used as a stepping point, the spill could still have been avoided  if the pool company would have followed procedure and ensured that the main valve was being closed  at the end of business each day. The tank would have been filled by the driver according to standard  procedure, and the pool company staff would have discovered the leak when they started working as they  attempted to open the main valve.

column168: TRI ISLAND ENERGY DELIVERED 7000 GALLONS OF REGULAR GASOLINE UN1203 TO TANK #2 WHICH HAS A COMBINED OF 24,000 GALLONS WITH TANK 3 (2 - 12,000 GALLON TANKS MANIFOLDED TOGETHER). THE STARTING BALANCE WAS 4000 GALLONS LEAVING MORE THAN SUFFICIENT ROOM TO UNLOAD THE 7000 GALLONS OF REGULAR. THE TANKS ARE IN A LOCKED AND VAULTED CONTAINMENT LOADED FROM A SPILL CONTAINMENT BOX LOCATED OUTSIDE THE VAULT. TANKS HAVE A FRANKLIN FUEL MONITORING SYSTEM AND AN OPW OVERFILL VALVE ON EACH TANK. DRIVER COMPLETE DELIVERY, DISCONNECTED HOSE. AS HE PREPARING TO LEAVE HE NOTICED RED LIQUID (REGULAR GAS) SEEPING FROM GROUND CLOSE TO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT WALL. IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED GAS STATION MANAGER AND THEY SHUT DOWN GAS STATION. FIRST THOUGHT WHERE TANK FAILURE, MONITOR AND OR HIGH LEVEL SHUT OFF FAILURE. GAS STATION MANAGER UNLOCKED VAULT AND UPON INSPECTION. NO TANK FAILURE, NO SIGNS OF TANK OVERFILL OR TANK MONITOR FAILURE. APPROX FIVE GALLONS OF GASOLINE ON CONTAINMENT FLOOR BUT EXTREME VAPORS. GAS STATION MANAGER CALLED FIRE DEPARTMENT & DPNR (EPA). FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED AREA DUE TO FUMES. THE TANK WAS NOT OVERFILLED, NO VISIBLE LEAKS. FIRE DEPARTMENT FOAMED DOWN TANK IN CONTAINMENT VAULT #2 TO ELIMINATE VAPOR DANGER. UPON FILLING THE CONTAINMENT WITH FOAM AND WATER THE LEAK IN THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT WAS VERY VISIBLE.

column168: Upon arrival at unloading point, a Martin Transport driver removed the dust cap from the bottom outlet valve.  Product began spraying out of the outlet piping striking the driver and another Martin employee standing nearby.  The driver was protected by PPE but the Martin observor was not wearing PPE.  The driver immediately activated the emergency shut off, stopping the flow of product.  Both employees then entered a safety shower.  Both employees were transported to the hospital for examination and treatment.  The driver was treated and released.  The observor was admitted for treatment of acid burns.    Upon investigation it was discovered that both the internal valve and bottom outlet valve were left open following a trailer wash prior to the trailer being loaded.
column169: All employees were briefed on the incident in a training session.  The importance of wearing proper PPE and verifying all valves are closed prior to loading or removing a dust cap were key items of the training.
